                            jump to other results
                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" hclass="sense" id="abolitionism_sng_1" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" hclass="sensetop" htag="span"><span class="def" hclass="def" htag="span">the American campaign in the 1800s to end the system of <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/slavery" title="slavery definition"><span class="ndv">slavery</span></a> in the southern states. Its members were called <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/abolitionist#abolitionist_topg_1" title="abolitionists definition"><span class="ndv">abolitionists</span></a>, and many hid <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/enslave" title="enslaved definition"><span class="ndv">enslaved</span></a> people who were escaping on the <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/the-underground-railroad#the_underground_railroad_topg_1" title="Underground Railroad definition"><span class="ndv">Underground Railroad</span></a>. Famous abolitionists included the poet <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/john-greenleaf-whittier" title="John Greenleaf Whittier definition"><span class="ndv">John Greenleaf Whittier</span></a> and the author <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/harriet-beecher-stowe" title="Harriet Beecher Stowe definition"><span class="ndv">Harriet Beecher Stowe</span></a>.</span></span>    <div id="ring-links-box">
